04861nam a22005415i 9780520924178DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209241787 a10.1525/97805209241782doi  a(DE-B1597)648508  a(OCoLC)1419790207  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPER0040002bisacsh1 aHorton, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWriting the Character-Centered Screenplay, Updated and Expanded edition /cAndrew Horton; ed. by Andrew Horton. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (249 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: CHARACTER -- tChapter One: The Feast of Becoming: Carnival and Character -- tChapter Two: Varieties of Voices Within Character -- tChapter Three: Five Not-So-Easy Pieces: Analysis of Character-Centered Scripts -- tPART II: NARRATIVE AND STRUCTURE -- tChapter Four: Beyond the Classical Hollywood Structure -- tChapter Five: Developing a Character-Centered Narrative -- tChapter Six: Pitching -- tPART III: WRITING -- tChapter Seven: Prelude to a Screenplay -- tChapter Eight: The Fourteen-Week Character Developing Schedule -- tChapter Nine: The Fourteen-Week Feature Screenplay -- tPART IV: LAUNCHING YOUR SCRIPT -- tChapter Ten: From Rewrite to Screen: An Overview of Options -- tChapter Eleven: Live Writers Talking: Screenwriting 2000 and Beyond -- tAppendix A: Coverage -- tAppendix B: Self-Critiques -- tAppendix C: Your Personal Screenwriting and Video Library -- tAppendix D: At Long Last the Recipe for a Screenwriter's Gumbo with Character! -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe need good screenwriters who understand character. Everywhere Andrew Horton traveled in researching this book—from Hollywood to Hungary—he heard the same refrain. Yet most of the standard how-to books on screenwriting follow the film industry's earlier lead in focusing almost exclusively on plot and formulaic structures.With this book, Horton, a film scholar and successful screenwriter, provides the definitive work on the character-based screenplay. Exceptionally wide-ranging—covering American, international, mainstream, and "off-Hollywood" films, as well as television—the book offers creative strategies and essential practical information.Horton begins by placing screenwriting in the context of the storytelling tradition, arguing through literary and cultural analysis that all great stories revolve around a strong central character. He then suggests specific techniques and concepts to help any writer—whether new or experienced—build more vivid characters and screenplays. Centering his discussion around four film examples—including Thelma & Louise and The Silence of the Lambs—and the television series, Northern Exposure, he takes the reader step-by-step through the screenwriting process, starting with the development of multi-dimensional characters and continuing through to rewrite. Finally, he includes a wealth of information about contests, fellowships, and film festivals.Espousing a new, character-based approach to screenwriting, this engaging, insightful work will prove an essential guide to all of those involved in the writing and development of film scripts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm. 4aGeneral. 4aPerforming Arts. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aHorton, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022165940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092417840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520924178423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520924178/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles